        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "QoI relevance acceptance criteria — NIH as clinical surrogate",
        "description": "The primary QoI (normalized index of hemolysis, NIH) must be formally linked to the clinical endpoint (chronic hemolysis risk) via a documented mechanistic or empirical relationship. The relationship must be cited from peer-reviewed literature or regulatory guidance. Secondary QoIs (shear stress, exposure time) must be shown to drive the primary QoI."
      },
      "rationale": "NIH is the FDA-accepted surrogate for hemolysis risk per FDA Guidance (2017). Mechanistic linkage via the Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law model (J. Heart Valve Dis. 1990) and subsequent Arora et al. (Ann. Biomed. Eng. 2004) calibration is documented. Sensitivity analysis confirms that volume-averaged scalar shear stress and Lagrangian exposure time are the dominant drivers of NIH (see hasSensitivityAnalysis)."
    },
